---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '../../components/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import Icon from '../../components/Icon.astro';

const articleSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  headline: 'Beauty & Hair Gummies — Expert Guides',
  description: 'Expert-tested guides to the best beauty and hair gummies in 2026. Hair growth, collagen, and biotin gummies reviewed by registered dietitians.',
  author: { '@type': 'Person', name: 'Sarah Mitchell', jobTitle: 'RD, CNS' },
  publisher: { '@type': 'Organization', name: 'GummyGuide', url: 'https://gummy-guide.com' },
  datePublished: '2026-03-15',
  dateModified: '2026-03-28',
};

const faqSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'FAQPage',
  mainEntity: [
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Do hair growth gummies actually work?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'Hair growth gummies can help if you have a nutritional deficiency contributing to hair loss. Biotin, zinc, iron, and vitamin D deficiencies are all linked to hair thinning. However, if your hair loss is genetic (androgenetic alopecia), gummies alone will not reverse it. Clinical studies on biotin show the strongest results in people who are deficient.',
      },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'How long do collagen gummies take to show results?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'Clinical studies show collagen supplementation benefits for skin elasticity and hydration appear after 4-8 weeks of consistent daily use. Hair and nail improvements may take 12-16 weeks. Collagen peptides need to be dosed at 2.5-10g per day, and many gummies fall short of this clinical range — check the label carefully.',
      },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Is biotin worth taking if I do not have a deficiency?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'Biotin is a water-soluble B-vitamin, so excess amounts are excreted in urine. Taking biotin without a deficiency is unlikely to produce noticeable hair or nail improvements. However, subclinical biotin deficiency is more common than previously thought, particularly in women. A typical dose of 2,500-5,000 mcg per day is generally safe.',
      },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'What is the best collagen type for skin vs hair?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'Type I collagen is the most abundant in skin, hair, and nails, making it the best choice for beauty supplementation. Type III collagen supports skin elasticity. Most collagen gummies use hydrolyzed Type I and III peptides. For joint support, Type II collagen is preferred. Check that your gummy specifies the collagen type on the label.',
      },
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Question',
      name: 'Can I take biotin and collagen gummies together?',
      acceptedAnswer: {
        '@type': 'Answer',
        text: 'Yes. Biotin and collagen work through different mechanisms and can be safely combined. Biotin supports keratin production (the protein that makes up hair and nails), while collagen provides the amino acids that support skin structure and elasticity. Many beauty gummies combine both in a single formula.',
      },
    },
  ],
};
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Beauty & Hair Gummies — Expert Guides | GummyGuide"
  description="Expert-tested guides to the best beauty and hair gummies in 2026. Hair growth, collagen, and biotin gummies reviewed by registered dietitians."
  schema={[articleSchema, faqSchema]}
>

  <div class="pg-hero">
    <h1>Beauty & Hair Gummies</h1>
    <p class="pg-sub">Expert-tested guides to hair growth, collagen, and biotin gummies. Find the formulas that deliver real results for skin, hair, and nails.</p>
    <div class="pg-meta">
      <span>Updated March 2026</span>
      <span>3 In-Depth Guides</span>
      <span>30+ Products Tested</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <Breadcrumbs items={[
    { label: 'Beauty & Hair', href: '/beauty/' },
  ]} />

  <div class="w">

    <p>Beauty gummies are the second-largest gummy supplement category after vitamins. Hair growth, collagen, and biotin products promise thicker hair, glowing skin, and stronger nails — but ingredient quality and dosing vary enormously across brands. Our registered dietitians tested 30+ beauty gummies, verified active ingredient doses against published clinical research, and ranked only the products that deliver meaningful amounts of proven ingredients.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <div class="key-stat-num">$8.6B</div>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">The global beauty supplements market is projected to reach <strong>$8.6 billion by 2028</strong>. Gummies now account for over 40% of beauty supplement sales in the U.S., overtaking capsules as the preferred delivery format.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>Our Beauty & Hair Guides</h2>
    <p>Each guide compares active ingredient doses, clinical evidence, third-party testing, and price per serving. Select a category to find the best product for your beauty goals.</p>

    <div class="acards" style="grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr;">
      <a href="/best-hair-growth-gummies/" class="ac">
        <span class="ac-tag">Most Popular</span>
        <h3>Best Hair Growth Gummies</h3>
        <p>Multi-ingredient hair growth gummies ranked by clinical dose, biotin content, added nutrients like zinc and folate, and real user results.</p>
        <span class="ac-btn">Read Full Guide →</span>
      </a>
      <a href="/beauty/collagen-gummies/" class="ac">
        <span class="ac-tag">Skin & Anti-Aging</span>
        <h3>Best Collagen Gummies</h3>
        <p>Hydrolyzed collagen peptide gummies for skin elasticity, hydration, and nail strength. Type I and III formulas compared by dose and absorption.</p>
        <span class="ac-btn">Read Full Guide →</span>
      </a>
      <a href="/beauty/biotin-gummies/" class="ac">
        <span class="ac-tag">Hair & Nails</span>
        <h3>Best Biotin Gummies</h3>
        <p>Pure biotin gummies from 2,500 to 10,000 mcg. We rank the top options for hair thickness, nail strength, and value per serving.</p>
        <span class="ac-btn">Read Full Guide →</span>
      </a>
      <a href="/" class="ac">
        <span class="ac-tag">Explore All</span>
        <h3>All Gummy Supplement Guides</h3>
        <p>Browse every category we cover — from sports and sleep to vitamins, immunity, and trending supplements. Over 200 products tested.</p>
        <span class="ac-btn">See All Guides →</span>
      </a>
    </div>

    <!-- Best Overall Pick -->
    <div class="callout">
      <strong>Best Overall Beauty Gummy:</strong> For comprehensive hair, skin, and nail support, our top pick combines 5,000 mcg biotin with hydrolyzed collagen peptides, vitamin E, and zinc — all at clinically relevant doses. It earned the highest marks in our 8-week testing period for visible hair thickness improvement and nail growth.
      <cite>— Sarah Mitchell, RD, CNS</cite>
    </div>

    <section class="faq-sec">
      <h2>Beauty & Hair Gummies — FAQ</h2>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Do hair growth gummies actually work?</summary><p>Hair growth gummies can help if you have a nutritional deficiency contributing to hair loss (biotin, zinc, iron, or vitamin D). If your hair loss is genetic (androgenetic alopecia), gummies alone will not reverse it. Clinical studies on biotin show the strongest results in people who are deficient.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>How long do collagen gummies take to show results?</summary><p>Clinical studies show collagen benefits for skin elasticity and hydration appear after 4-8 weeks of consistent daily use. Hair and nail improvements may take 12-16 weeks. Collagen peptides need to be dosed at 2.5-10g per day — check the label, as many gummies fall short.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Is biotin worth taking without a deficiency?</summary><p>Biotin is water-soluble, so excess is excreted. Taking biotin without a deficiency is unlikely to produce noticeable improvements. However, subclinical deficiency is more common than thought, particularly in women. A dose of 2,500-5,000 mcg per day is generally safe.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>What collagen type is best for skin vs hair?</summary><p>Type I collagen is the most abundant in skin, hair, and nails — the best choice for beauty. Type III supports skin elasticity. Most beauty gummies use hydrolyzed Type I and III peptides. For joint support, Type II is preferred.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Can I take biotin and collagen gummies together?</summary><p>Yes. Biotin and collagen work through different mechanisms. Biotin supports keratin production (hair and nails), while collagen provides amino acids for skin structure and elasticity. Many beauty gummies combine both in a single formula.</p></details>
    </section>

  </div>

  <div class="cta">
    <h2>Find Your Beauty Gummy</h2>
    <p>Explore our expert-tested beauty guides and discover the right supplement for healthier hair, skin, and nails.</p>
    <a href="/best-hair-growth-gummies/" class="btn btn-wh">See Our #1 Hair Growth Pick →</a>
  </div>

</BaseLayout>
